    {
      "id": "55afc61e8aedd22110cc3273a898033d60b4d731",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2011-11-15 10:00:37.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\n(1 inline comment)\n\nBruce,\nI just noticed this patch after I sent my previous email, sorry for the confusion.\n\nIf these patches are all independent changes, they need to be submitted as separate changes.  There are two ways to do this with Gerrit:\n\n1) make a separate branch for each patch.  If the patches are all independent, and do not necessarily have to be landed in order, this is the best way since it actually allows them to be inspected, tested, and landed in any order, and doesn't block all of the changes if there is an objection to one part of the code.  This requires creating a bunch of branches in your own tree, but that is very simple:\n\n$ git checkout -b b_smallfix1 master\n{do one change}\n$ git commit {files}\n$ git push ...\n$ git checkout -b b_smallfix2 master\n{do another change}\n$ git commit {files}\n$ git push ...\n :\n :\n\n2) make a patch series with all the independent changes on the same branch.  This is a tiny bit less effort, but has the drawback that if one of the earlier patches fails (build or inspection or testing) then all of the later changes have to be resubmitted, even if they already had posivive inspections and testing was completed.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
